{"id":"1711.10570","submitter":"Kipton Barros","authors":"Zhentao Wang, Gia-Wei Chern, Cristian D. Batista, Kipton Barros","title":"Gradient-based stochastic estimation of the density matrix","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.5017741","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Fast estimation of the single-particle density matrix is key to many\napplications in quantum chemistry and condensed matter physics. The best\nnumerical methods leverage the fact that the density matrix elements\n$f(H)_{ij}$ decay rapidly with distance $r_{ij}$ between orbitals. This decay\nis usually exponential. However, for the special case of metals at zero\ntemperature, algebraic decay of the density matrix appears and poses a\nsignificant numerical challenge. We introduce a gradient-based probing method\nto estimate all local density matrix elements at a computational cost that\nscales linearly with system size. For zero-temperature metals the stochastic\nerror scales like $S^{-(d+2)/2d}$, where $d$ is the dimension and $S$ is a\nprefactor to the computational cost. The convergence becomes exponential if the\nsystem is at finite temperature or is insulating.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 28 Nov 2017 21:38:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 13 Apr 2018 23:16:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-04-17"}
